<span class="comment"><font color=#000000>This is the broken window fallacy [1]. If the company didn't have to pay developers to maintain bad code, they could invest that money in something more economically useful, like new products.<p>[1] <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Broken_window_fallacy" rel="nofollow">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Broken_window_fallacy</a></font></span><p><font size=1><font color=#f6f6ef>-----</font></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table border=0><tr><td><img src="http://ycombinator.com/images/s.gif" height=1 width=120></td><td valign=top><center><a id=up_2038745 href="vote?for=2038745&dir=up&whence=%2f%78%3f%66%6e%69%64%3d%77%74%33%6d%75%68%72%64%50%33"><img src="http://ycombinator.com/images/grayarrow.gif" border=0 vspace=3 hspace=2></a><span id=down_2038745></span></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px; "><span class="comhead"><a href="user?id=towelrod">towelrod</a> 406 days ago  | <a href="item?id=2038745">link</a></span></div><br>
